To help prepare our Bulldogs for their upcoming first day of school - we are offering a variety of Chromebook pickup dates and times - choose any location or date that works best for you!
ALL MAROON AND GOLD STUDENTS MUST HAVE A DEVICE! If your student needs a device, a parent may come and pick up a district-owned Chromebook during these times.
You are welcome to bring your own Chromebook or laptop, you'll just need to set it up to work on our district wifi by following the directions on our website: https://buff.ly/317mndL
For Maroon Students, these devices will need to travel back and forth to school with you so that assignments can be completed via COVID-19 regulations.
Please contact us with any questions at restart2020@smfcsd.org!

**PLEASE NOTE: during all pick-ups we ask that you wear a mask and abide by social distancing protocol. Only one person per family, please.

Today Summit County Public Health released new recommendations for the opening of schools. Due to the requirement of 6' social distance for all students and additional requirements from the Ohio Department of Health (ODH) and Center for Disease Control (CDC), SMFCSD will be forced to now open in the new Orange/Red Status, which is our hybrid learning model, in the event Summit County is in Yellow, Orange or Red designation) at the time school starts. In order for SMFCSD to remain transparent with all of our families, please know that some level of risk will always be present when students and school district employees occupy school district facilities.

We recognize this change may result inâ€¦

post_text:
The Stow Munroe Falls Band Program conducts an annual "Tag Day" every year.
During this event, band students go into the neighborhoods of Munroe Falls and Stow, knock on doors, and ask for donations. It is our largest fundraiser of the year. The money students collect goes directly to the band and is used for students in grades 5-12.
Unfortunately, this spring, due to the pandemic, we were unable to carry out this event. Students would love to knock on your door and ask for your donations, but it is unsafe at this time. Weâ€™ve decided to take Tag Day online this year! Please click on the attached link and consider helping https://buff.ly/33hMaBc.
The band students thank you!

We understand and respect that our Bulldog families are working hard to finalize a decision for their student's 2020-2021 school year. We also realize that new information has been recently released and want to be sure our families have adequate time to make the decision that is right for them. Intent Forms are now due in FinalForms by August 3, 2020.

Please note: If you select the Maroon Plan with the intention of switching to the Gold Plan there will be up to a two week waiting period after the start of school before any moves to the Gold Plan can be made. If you have made your choice for a plan but need to switch this please contact us: restart2020@smfcsdorg.

Attention Stow-Munroe Falls Parents of 3-5 year olds that will not be going to kindergarten for the 20-21 school year: Lilâ€™ Bulldogs Preschool, housed at Indian Trail Elementary School, is currently looking for typically developing peer models to attend our Integrated Preschool Program for the 20-21 School Year. Preschool is 4 half-days per week (M-Th.), with no school on Fridays.
Tuition is very reasonable at $140 per month during the school year.
For consideration for screening, student must live within Stow or Munroe Falls School District attendance limits and must be able to be dropped off/picked up at preschool each school day.

PEER ROLE MODELS

Attention Stow-Munroe Falls Parents of 3-5 year olds that will not be going to kindergarten for the 20-21 school year: Lilâ€™ Bulldogs Preschool, housed at Indian Trail Elementary School, is currently looking for typically developing peer models to attend our Integrated Preschool Program for the 20-21 School Year. Preschool is 4 half-days per week (M-Th.), with no school on Fridays.
Tuition is very reasonable at $140 per month during the school year.
For consideration for screening, student must live within Stow or Munroe Falls School District attendance limits and must be able to be dropped off/picked up at preschool each school day.

PEER ROLE MODELS
Typical peer role models or childrenâ€¦

post_text: Join us in celebrating another awesome #SMFSundaySeniorSpotlight! Vincent Carbone is 4-year Honor Roll & Academic Letter Award winner ranked in the Top 4% of his class. He was 2-year Varsity Captain of Stow H.S. Volleyball team & their 2019 season MVP. He also won 2019 Honorable Mention for the Ohio Valley Region Volleyball Player & 4-time Academic Scholar Awards. He was the 2019 Stow Marching Band Percussion Section & Snare Squad Leader and served 2 years on National Honor Society, and a Freshman Mentor. Vincent is a graduate of Programming & Software Development (a two-year CTE program housed at SMFHS) and served as a Student Ambassador for the Six-District Educational Compact. He was also a 2-year member of the Technology Work Experience Program (Stow IT department). Vincent will be attending The Ohio State University this fall as a Computer Science & Engineering major. Way to go, Vincent! You make your #Classof2020 proud!

shared_text:
Shon Christy is with Dana Pisani.
May 11 at 8:05 AM Â·

Our educators in Stow are world class. Shout out to teacher Dana Pisani from Stow-Munroe Falls City School District who reached out to me with an idea to support 60 special students with these signs that were delivered over the weekend. We then assembled the dream team to get the work done. Thank you to Kelli R Smith (Life Is Good No Matter What) for their generous grant to pay for the signs, Cody Heeney for printing them quickly and discounted, and Molly Hartong for the donation of the design. Everyone came together quickly and generously to make students smile. Well done all!

post_text: On Saturday, May 2nd, SMFHS Programming & Software Development students presented their app inventions in a virtual showcase among other N.E. Ohio high schools. Five SMFHS teams presented every 15 minutes in various rooms via Zoom, and Carson Smith, Seth Lamancusa, and Mike Eckenrode won $600 for their ShopEz app. Students and their teacher (Mrs. Whitmer) formed a "huddle" in one of the Zoom rooms during break to touch base, and share tips and ideas amongst the teams.
